Shrak,

With the Imperial guard increasing its watch over the Market District, we of the Bloodhawks have had to increase our vigilance against their prying eyes.  We have relocated our base to a hidden sector of the city, and will no longer be able to directly contact you for new additions to our... stock.

For the time being, I have stationed two of my men at the Ravenclaw Tavern.  You may feel free to go to them should you have need to contact us, and they will take care of any business you may need to conduct with our organization.

I have instructed my men to use all caution when dealing with strangers, so be wary to follow my next instructions.  Upon need to contact us, go to the inn rooms at the Ravenclaw Tavern.  My men are residing in one of these rooms.  You must knock on the door three times, upon which one of the men will ask your business.  Tell him the phrase: "The hawk's blood flows freely...", and my men will know you to be an ally.  Do not forget this, for they shall not have any dealings with you otherwise!

I apologize for any troubles this may cause you, but we feel it necessary to take all precautions to avoid being discovered. 

- Jhordak

Irilium Crystals are strong and stable sources of magical power. It is common for these gems to be used as magical ingredients in a variety of spells and rituals.

Animating a construct is not a task to be taken lightly by those inexperienced in the arts of magic, but to those well versed in the arcane arts, constructs can prove to be great and devoted servants.  Properly created, constructs can aid in a variety of tasks at their master's command, from simple labor to fearsome allies in combat.

Once the initial construct is built, a task both expensive and complicated, it is necessary to find a power source to animate the construct.  For a stable source, it is strongly recommended that one use Irilium Crystals, often found in the southern lands of the Sharakhan Empire.  While a bit hard to come by in these northern frontier lands, Irilium is the only dependable source for animation of constructs, and other substitutes are discouraged.

Used in times of trouble, these priestly waters comfort the sorrowful and make great men of lowly cowards.
This tonic is sovereign against venoms, mineral toxins, diseases, and poisons of all sorts.
This thick concoction smells dark and musty, like a forest after heavy rains.
Called "portable priests" by more cynical adventurers, these holy infusions are of great use to the average adventurer.
These blood-red infusions, made from the horns and heart of young bulls, grant the drinker great physical strength.
This sparkling potion greatly increases the drinker's Dexterity.
Made of hot liquid poured over scorched and pungent beans, this strong-smelling brew did not get its name from its appearance. It helps clear and fortify the mind against spells that affect the mind.
With the power to return people from the very brink of death, these potions do not come cheaply.
Used as often in the peasant's home as the dungeon's dark, these simple concoctions are common throughout Abaran.
These curative potions are too expensive for most civilians, and are used almost exclusively by soldiers and adventurers.
With the power to staunch the flow of blood or knit a broken bone, these potions are in common use among the dangerous professions.
With their ability to smooth the complexion, gloss the hair, and brighten the eyes, these potions find regular use among the nobility. But it shall make anyone more comely.
A potion of endurance combines various magical components to increase stamina and overall health, though it does not heal damage.
These potions are eagerly sought by sages, scholars, and adventuring wizards alike. When imbibed, they grant a bonus to the drinker's Intelligence score.
These potions are in equal demand by adventurers and scholars, allowing for the imbiber to clear their thoughts in the pursuit of remembering vague legends and tales of old.
This milky red potion seems to open the drinker's perception of his environment, making him at once more observant and more resistant to effects that target the mind.

This pack contains enough food and water for a single day of adventuring. Most nobles and merchants use this sort of food pack while traveling out in the wilds of the empire. Though there are many other substitutes for traditional packed rations, this is the most popular choice of those that can afford it.

This item can be used as a ration. You will need to have some form of ration in your inventory to gain any benefit from resting.

Chakara berries are well known throughout the Sharakhan Empire for being far more nourishing than their size would suggest.  A handful of these berries is more than enough food to fill the belly of a grown man, and provides nourishment for a full day's worth of food. 

This item can be used as a ration. You will need to have some form of ration in your inventory to gain any benefit from resting.

Grahmin, a strange herd beast found in the rural areas of the Northern Reaches, carry all manner of edible parts on their body.  

Their tongues are widely known for making a delicious meal.

Juju nuts, taken from the Jujira plant, are often sought after by wilderness travellers.  Though not particularly filling, these nuts can make a good substitute for one's diet while away from civilized areas, being easy to carry while maintaining their freshness indefinitely.
